20of%20Criminal%20Procedure%2C%201973%20(CrPC)%20%E2%80%93%20first%2C%20whether%20the%20Enforcement%20Directorate%20(ED)%20is%20entitled%20to%20obtain%20an%20accused%E2%80%99s%20custody%20thereunder%3B%20and%20second%2C%20in%20case%20it%20is%2C%20whether%20such%20custody%20can%20be%20obtained%20when%20the%C2%A0first%2015%20days%20after%20arrest%20have%20elapsed.%20The%20court%20answered%20both%20questions%20in%20the%20affirmative%2C%20conferring%20upon%20the%20ED%20the%20power%20to%20obtain%20an%20accused%E2%80%99s%20custody%20despite%20its%20officers%20not%20constituting%20the%20police%2C%20and%20holding%20that%20the%20requirement%20of%20the%20first%2015%20days%20was%20so%20inextricably%20tied%20up%20with%20the%20facts%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findiankanoon.org%2Fdoc%2F244622%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3ECBI%20v.%20Anupam%20Kulkarni%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20it%20didn%E2%80%99t%20constitute%20a%20general%20binding%20rule.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20this%20piece%2C%20I%20discuss%20the%20court%E2%80%99s%20treatment%20of%20the%20issue%20of%20the%20ED%E2%80%99s%20power%20to%20obtain%20custody%2C%20proposing%20that%20the%20instant%20case%20has%20the%20effect%20of%20further%20constituting%20the%20ED%20as%20an%20entity%20highly%20illegible%20in%20law%2C%20which%20can%20conveniently%20shapeshift%20into%20different%20avatars%20based%20on%20the%20greatest%20rights-restrictive%20interpretation%20of%20the%20Prevention%20of%20Money%20Laundering%20Act%2C%202002%20(PMLA).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cins%3EAlso%20read%3A%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Fgovernment%2Fhow-the-enforcement-directorate-has-become-an-excessive-directorate%5C%22%3EHow%20the%20Enforcement%20Directorate%20Has%20Become%20an%20Excessive%20Directorate%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fins%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20make%20this%20argument%20in%20the%20following%20manner%20%E2%80%93%C2%A0%3Cem%3Efirst%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20I%20discuss%20the%20groundwork%20upon%20which%20the%20court%20was%20to%20decide%20the%20instant%20case%2C%20which%20concerned%20the%20binary%20of%20police%20and%20judicial%20custody%2C%20along%20with%20the%20ED%E2%80%99s%20divergence%20therewith%3B%20and%20%3Cem%3Esecond%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20based%20on%20this%20groundwork%2C%20I%20discuss%20the%20ED%E2%80%99s%20powers%20to%20obtain%20an%20accused%E2%80%99s%20custody%2C%20arguing%20that%20the%20unreasoned%20pursuit%20of%20an%20omnipotent%20ED%20is%20all%20that%20stands%20as%20reasoning.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EEntrenched%20binaries%20and%20institutions%20beyond%20binaries%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20powers%20of%20the%20ED%20to%20effect%20arrest%20are%20provided%20under%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findiankanoon.org%2Fdoc%2F1093594%2F%5C%22%3ESection%2019%20of%20the%20PMLA%2C%3C%2Fa%3E%20which%20requires%20superior%20ED%20officials%20to%20have%20a%20%E2%80%9Creason%20to%20believe%E2%80%9D%20in%20a%20person%E2%80%99s%20guilt.%20Pursuant%20to%20Section%2019(3)%20of%20the%20PMLA%2C%20all%20persons%20arrested%20must%20be%20presented%20before%20a%20judicial%20magistrate%20within%2024%20hours.%20The%20trajectory%20of%20events%20after%20the%20accused%E2%80%99s%C2%A0production%20before%20the%20magistrate%2C%20therefore%2C%20is%20in%20question.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CCustody%E2%80%9D%20%E2%80%93%20as%20explained%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findiankanoon.org%2Fdoc%2F154033650%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EGautam%20Navlakha%20v.%20NIA%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%93%20is%20the%20period%20for%20which%20the%20accused%20is%20present%20either%20exclusively%20with%20the%20police%20to%20allow%20them%20to%20undertake%20%E2%80%9Ccustodial%20interrogation%E2%80%9D%20or%20in%20a%20jail%2C%20where%20the%20police%20are%20ordinarily%20forbidden%20from%20entering%20and%20interrogating.%C2%A0This%20binary%20of%20police%20and%20judicial%20custody%20necessitates%20all%20forms%20of%20custody%20to%20fall%20under%20either%20two%20categories.%20As%20a%20corollary%2C%20it%20forbids%20custody%20to%20an%20entity%20%3Cem%3Enot%3C%2Fem%3E%20constituting%20either%20the%20court%20or%20the%20police%2C%20which%20is%20commonsensically%20derivable%20from%20the%20text%20of%20Section%20167(2)%20and%20is%20fairly%20entrenched%20in%20case%20law.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20text%20of%20Section%20167(2)%20equips%20the%20magistrate%20to%20detain%20an%20accused%20in%20%E2%80%9Csuch%20custody%20as%20he%20thinks%20fit%E2%80%9D%2C%20while%20the%20first%20proviso%20thereto%20states%20that%20%3Cem%3Eonly%3C%2Fem%3E%20custody%20%E2%80%9Cotherwise%20than%20in%20custody%20of%20the%20police%E2%80%9D%20may%20exceed%2015%20days.%20The%20term%20%E2%80%9Cotherwise%20than%20in%20the%20custody%20of%20the%20police%E2%80%9D%2C%20it%20must%20be%20noted%2C%20can%20%3Cem%3Eonly%3C%2Fem%3E%20mean%20judicial%20custody%2C%20for%20there%20is%20no%20actor%20other%20than%20the%20police%20or%20the%20court%20that%20can%20obtain%20the%20accused%E2%80%99s%20custody.%20This%20proposition%20can%20be%20verified%20both%20from%20the%20design%20of%20other%20laws%20that%20forego%20this%20twisted%20terminology%2C%20as%20well%20as%20case%20law%20that%20attempts%20to%20fit%20all%20kinds%20of%20custody%20of%20the%20accused%20within%20these%20two%20categories.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Prevention%20of%20Terrorism%20Act%2C%202002%2C%20for%20example%2C%20contained%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findiankanoon.org%2Fdoc%2F742110%2F%5C%22%3ESection%2049(2)(b)%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20amended%20Section%20167(2)%20of%20the%20CrPC%20for%20offences%20committed%20under%20the%20former%2C%20creating%20a%20regime%20for%20shifting%20an%20accused%20to%20%E2%80%9Cpolice%20custody%20from%20judicial%20custody%E2%80%9D.%20This%20amendment%20was%20upheld%20by%20the%20Supreme%20Court%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findiankanoon.org%2Fdoc%2F699436%2F%23%3A~%3Atext%3DOn%252027.2.%2Cconnection%2520with%2520the%2520alleged%2520occurrence.%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EMaulavi%20Hussein%20Haji%20Abraham%20Umarji%20v.%20State%20of%20Gujarat%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20with%20the%20court%20noting%20that%20%E2%80%9Cthe%20acceptance%20of%20application%20for%20police%20custody%20when%20an%20accused%20is%20in%20judicial%20custody%20is%20not%20a%20matter%20of%20course%E2%80%9D%20%5B25%5D.%20A%20similar%20regime%20of%20shifting%20custody%20is%20provided%20u%2Fs%2043D(2)(b)%20of%20the%20Unlawful%20Activities%20(Prevention)%20Act%2C%201967%2C%20which%20again%20creates%20a%20regime%20for%20shifting%20custody%2C%20noting%20the%20existence%20%3Cem%3Eonly%3C%2Fem%3E%20of%20police%20and%20judicial%20custody%20%E2%80%93%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E%E2%80%9CProvided%E2%80%A6that%20if%20the%20police%20officer%20making%20the%20investigation%E2%80%A6requests%2C%20for%20the%20purposes%20of%20investigation%2C%20for%20police%20custody%20from%20judicial%20custody%C2%A0of%20any%20person%20in%20judicial%20custody%2C%20he%20shall%20file%20an%20affidavit%E2%80%A6%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EFurther%2C%20proviso%20(b)%20to%20Section%20167(2)%20expressly%20notes%20the%20binary%20of%20police%20and%20judicial%20custody%2C%20forbidding%20the%20magistrate%20from%20approving%20police%20custody%20for%20an%20accused%20who%20wasn%E2%80%99t%20physically%20produced%20before%20them.%20Even%20in%20%3Cem%3EGautam%20Navlakha%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20it%20must%20be%20noted%20that%20the%20issue%20solely%20concerned%20the%20characterisation%20of%20house%20arrest%20as%20either%20police%20or%20judicial%20custody%20%E2%80%93%20for%20only%20such%20characterisation%20would%20have%20the%20effect%20of%20making%20the%20accused%20eligible%20to%20obtain%20default%20bail%20under%20Section%20167(2)%20%5B107%5D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F07%2F21161633%2F2022_7img21_Jul_2022_PTI07_21_2022_000078B.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%221200%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F07%2F21161633%2F2022_7img21_Jul_2022_PTI07_21_2022_000078B.jpg%201200w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F07%2F21161633%2F2022_7img21_Jul_2022_PTI07_21_2022_000078B-300x200.jpg%20300w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F07%2F21161633%2F2022_7img21_Jul_2022_PTI07_21_2022_000078B-1024x682.jpg%201024w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-609187%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22799%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3ECongress%20MPs%20holding%20banner%20and%20placards%20stage%20a%20protest%20march%20at%20Parliament%20House%20complex%20to%20express%20their%20solidarity%20with%20the%20party%20Chief%20Sonia%20Gandhi%20who%20has%20to%20appear%20before%20the%20Enforcement%20Directorate%20in%20connection%20with%20the%20National%20Herald%20case%2C%20in%20New%20Delhi%2C%20July%2021%2C%202022.%20Photo%3A%20PTI%2FKamal%20Kishore%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIt%20is%20clear%2C%20therefore%2C%20that%20the%20provisos%20to%20Section%20167(2)%20envision%20only%20%E2%80%9Cpolice%20custody%E2%80%9D%2C%20and%20%E2%80%9Ccustody%20otherwise%20in%20the%20custody%20of%20the%20police%E2%80%9D%20(interpreted%20as%20judicial%20custody)%2C%20forbidding%20the%20magistrate%20from%20authorising%20the%20alternative%20forms%20of%20custody%20of%20the%20accused%2C%20with%20entities%20that%20aren%E2%80%99t%20the%20police%20or%20the%20court.%20On%20this%20basis%2C%20in%20case%20the%20ED%20seeks%20to%20obtain%20the%20accused%E2%80%99s%20custody%2C%20it%20must%20demonstrate%20its%20character%20either%20as%20the%20police%20or%20as%20a%20court.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EHere%20lies%20the%20problem%20%E2%80%93%20the%20Supreme%20Court%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findiankanoon.org%2Fdoc%2F14485072%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3EVijay%20Madanlal%20Choudhary%20vs%20Union%20of%20India%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20in%20order%20to%20bolster%20the%20strength%20of%20the%20ED%20to%20obtain%20confessions%20and%20make%20them%20relevant%20under%20Section%2025%20of%20the%20Indian%20Evidence%20Act%2C%201872%20(IEA)%20%E2%80%93%20specifically%20held%20that%20%E2%80%9Cit%20is%20unfathomable%20as%20to%20how%20the%20authorities%20%5Bof%20the%20ED%5D%E2%80%A6can%20be%20described%20as%20police%20of%EF%AC%81cer%E2%80%9D%2C%20relying%20on%20unsatisfactory%20case%20law%20whose%20standards%20require%20an%20identity%20of%20functions%20between%20the%20impugned%20agency%20and%20the%20police%20for%20the%20former%20to%20qualify%20as%20such%20%5B438%5D.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20court%20also%20upheld%20the%20constitutionality%20of%20Section%2050%20of%20the%20PMLA%20that%20confers%20upon%20the%20ED%20%3Cem%3Ejudicial%3C%2Fem%3E%20powers%20of%20examining%20witnesses%2C%20with%20lying%20to%20the%20ED%20punishable%20with%20up%20to%20seven%20years%20in%20prison%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findiankanoon.org%2Fdoc%2F308396%2F%5C%22%3Eunder%20Section%20193%20of%20the%20Indian%20Penal%20Code%2C%201860%3C%2Fa%3E.%20On%20this%20basis%2C%20the%20court%20noted%20that%20the%20ED%20dons%20a%20judicial%20hat%20at%20the%20summoning%20stage%20u%2Fs%2050.%20At%20the%20same%20time%2C%20however%2C%20the%20court%20held%20that%20if%20a%20confession%20was%20obtained%20post-arrest%2C%20the%20judicial%20hat%20is%20lost%2C%20and%20the%20confession%20again%20becomes%20irrelevant%20under%20Section%2025%20of%20the%20IEA%2C%20observing%20the%20following%20%E2%80%93%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E431.%20%E2%80%9C%E2%80%A6However%2C%20if%20his%2Fher%20statement%20is%20recorded%20after%20a%20formal%20arrest%20by%20the%20ED%20of%EF%AC%81cial%2C%20the%20consequences%20of%20Article%2020(3)%20or%20Section%2025%20of%20the%20Evidence%20Act%20may%20come%20into%20play%20to%20urge%20that%20the%20same%20being%20in%20the%20nature%20of%20confession%2C%20shall%20not%20be%20proved%20against%20him.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESince%20Section%2025%20of%20the%20IEA%20expressly%20uses%20the%20term%20%E2%80%9Cpolice%20officer%E2%80%9D%20to%20negate%20the%20relevance%20of%20confessions%2C%20the%20only%20way%20in%20which%20a%20confession%20can%20be%20irrelevant%20post-arrest%20is%20if%20the%20entity%20obtaining%20it%20%3Cem%3Ebecomes%3C%2Fem%3E%20a%20police%20officer.%20The%20court%20held%2C%20effectively%2C%20that%20the%20ED%20loses%20its%20judicial%20hat%20%3Cem%3Eafter%3C%2Fem%3E%20it%20arrests%2C%20now%20becoming%20the%20police.%20While%20this%20observation%20doesn%E2%80%99t%20sit%20well%20with%20the%20court%E2%80%99s%20holding%20that%20the%20ED%20generally%20doesn%E2%80%99t%20constitute%20the%20police%2C%20an%20alternative%20construction%20attracting%20the%20applicability%20of%20Section%2025%20is%20unlikely.%20On%20this%20basis%2C%20the%20ED%20is%20a%20court%20for%20summoning%20purposes%2C%20the%20police%20for%20arresting%20purposes%20%E2%80%93%20and%20yet%2C%20isn%E2%80%99t%20really%20the%20police.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EEscaping%20Binaries%20%E2%80%93%20%3Cem%3ESenthil%20Balaji%3C%2Fem%3E%20on%20ED%20custody%C2%A0%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20above%20was%20the%20groundwork%20for%20the%20court%20to%20navigate%20in%20%3Cem%3ESenthil%20Balaji%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20implying%20that%20it%20could%20either%20have%20held%20that%20the%20ED%2C%20not%20being%20the%20police%20generally%2C%20could%20not%20obtain%20custody%20for%20the%20purposes%20of%20interrogation%2C%20or%20it%20could%20employ%20%3Cem%3EChoudhary%E2%80%99s%3C%2Fem%3E%20observations%20on%20the%20post-arrest%20(police)%20character%20of%20the%20ED%2C%20making%20it%20eligible%20to%20obtain%20custody.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Supreme%20Court%20%E2%80%93%20along%20with%20two%20judges%20of%20the%20Madras%20high%20court%20%E2%80%93%20chose%20%3Cem%3Eneither%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20instead%20holding%20that%20Section%20167(2)%20doesn%E2%80%99t%20create%20a%20binary%20between%20police%20and%20judicial%20custody%20at%20all.%20The%20court%20held%20%E2%80%93%20interpreting%20Section%20167(2)%20divorced%20from%20provisos%20(a)%2C%20(b)%20and%20(c)%20%E2%80%93%20that%20the%20presence%20of%20the%20words%20%E2%80%9Csuch%20custody%E2%80%9D%20therein%20obviates%20the%20requirement%20of%20the%20custody-obtaining%20entity%20being%20the%20police%20%E2%80%93%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E85.%20%E2%80%9COne%20shall%20not%20confuse%20such%20powers%20conferred%20under%20the%20statute%20with%20the%20police%20power%2C%20however%2C%20when%20it%20comes%20to%20application%20of%20Section%20167(2)%20of%20the%20CrPC%2C%201973%20such%20an%20authority%20has%20to%20be%20brought%20under%20the%20expression%20%E2%80%9Csuch%20custody%E2%80%9D%20especially%20when%20the%20words%20%E2%80%9Cpolice%20custody%E2%80%9D%20are%20consciously%20omitted.%20Therefore%2C%20the%20ratio%20laid%20down%20in%20Vijay%20Madanlal%20Choudhary%20(supra)%20has%20to%20be%20understood%20contextually%2C%20in%20its%20own%20perspective.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20words%20%E2%80%9Cpolice%20custody%E2%80%9D%20and%20%E2%80%9Cjudicial%20custody%E2%80%9D%2C%20as%20Abhinav%20has%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheproofofguilt.blogspot.com%2F2023%2F08%2Fthe-judgment-in-v-senthil-balaji-v.html%5C%22%3Enoted%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20though%20absent%20from%20the%20body%20of%20Section%20167(2)%2C%20are%20present%20under%20both%20provisos.%20The%20structure%20of%20Section%20167(2)%20is%20such%20that%20the%20provisos%20become%20determinative%20of%20the%20kinds%20of%20custody%20that%20can%20be%20allowed%20%E2%80%93%C2%A0this%20is%20because%20while%20the%20body%20empowers%20the%20Magistrate%20to%20allow%20%E2%80%9Csuch%20custody%20as%20he%20thinks%20fit%E2%80%9D%2C%20proviso%20(a)%20states%20that%20he%20can%20allow%20custody%20%3Cem%3Ewithout%20the%20police%3C%2Fem%3E%20beyond%20fifteen%20days%2C%20meaning%20that%20he%20can%20allow%20custody%3Cem%3E%20with%20the%20police%3C%2Fem%3E%20only%20for%20fifteen%20days.%20As%20discussed%20above%2C%20proviso%20(b)%20states%20that%20while%20police%20custody%20can%20only%20be%20authorized%20only%20through%20the%20accused%E2%80%99s%20physical%20production%20in%20court%2C%20judicial%20custody%20can%20be%20authorized%20through%20the%20accused%E2%80%99s%20online%20production%2C%20and%20proviso%20(c)%20states%20that%20no%20second-class%20Magistrate%20can%20authorize%20police%20custody.%20It%20is%20clearly%20discernible%20that%20Section%20167(2)%20is%20wholly%20premised%20on%20the%20distinction%20between%20police%20and%20judicial%20custody%2C%20and%20does%20not%20envision%20custody%20beyond%20these%20categories.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBalaji%2C%20the%20accused%20under%20Section%204%20of%20the%20PMLA%2C%20made%20another%20argument%20on%20the%20basis%20of%20the%20scheme%20of%20the%20PMLA%20and%20CrPC%20before%20the%20Madras%20HC%20%E2%80%93%20he%20argued%20that%20the%20threshold%20of%20arrest%20u%2Fs%2019%20of%20the%20PMLA%20is%20that%20of%20a%20%E2%80%9Creason%20to%20believe%E2%80%9D%20accused%E2%80%99s%20guilt%2C%20and%20the%20ED%20can%20obtain%20such%20reasons%20only%20through%20the%20interrogation%20it%20undertakes%20at%20the%20summoning%20stage%20u%2Fs%2050.%20Pursuant%20to%20%3Cem%3EChoudhary%20%3C%2Fem%3E(and%20contrary%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findiankanoon.org%2Fdoc%2F1938988%2F%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3ENandini%20Satpathy%20v.%20P.L.%20Dani%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E)%2C%20the%20individual%20summoned%20before%20the%20ED%20u%2Fs%2050%20doesn%E2%80%99t%20enjoy%20a%20right%20to%20remain%20silent%2C%20and%20a%20refusal%20to%20cooperate%20through%20uttering%20false%20information%20constitutes%20an%20independent%20offence.%20On%20this%20basis%2C%20Balaji%20argued%20that%20if%20one%20has%20already%20undergone%20interrogation%20where%20one%20was%20legally%20bound%20to%20tell%20the%20truth%2C%20and%20based%20on%20such%20interrogation%20(and%20other%20investigation)%2C%20the%20ED%20had%20%E2%80%9Creasons%20to%20believe%E2%80%9D%20that%20he%20was%20guilty%2C%20what%20purpose%20could%20be%20served%20by%20further%20custodial%20interrogation%20through%20post-arrest%20ED%20custody%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.livelaw.in%2Fpdf_upload%2Fcvkj-order-dt-147-481387.pdf%5C%22%3Etie-breaker%20judgement%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20the%20Madras%20HC%2C%20however%2C%20repelled%20this%20contention%2C%20holding%20that%20there%20was%20%E2%80%9Cone%20small%20fallacy%20in%20the%E2%80%A6argument%E2%80%9D%20%5B136%5D%2C%20which%20is%20the%20following%20%E2%80%93%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E145.%20%E2%80%9COnce%20it%20is%20stated%20that%20the%20Code%20of%20Criminal%20Procedure%20applies%2C%20then%20these%20persons%2C%20namely%2C%20the%20Director%2C%20the%20Deputy%20Director%2C%20the%20Assistant%20Director%2C%20who%20are%20not%20police%20officials%20can%20take%20advantage%20of%20every%20provision%20under%20the%20Code%20of%20Criminal%20Procedure%20to%20obtain%2C%20in%20their%20opinion%20a%20logical%20conclusion%20to%20the%20trial%20process.%20If%20that%20step%20requires%20further%20investigation%20then%20they%20have%20every%20right%20to%20seek%20custody.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20%E2%80%9Cfallacy%E2%80%9D%2C%20according%20to%20the%20Madras%20HC%2C%20is%20that%20even%20though%20the%20ED%20has%20all%20possible%20resources%20to%20definitively%20pinpoint%20one%E2%80%99s%20guilt%20before%20effecting%20arrest%2C%20they%20should%20still%20be%20able%20to%20seek%20custody%2C%20because%20%3Cem%3Eit%20is%20their%20right%3C%2Fem%3E.%20This%20reference%20to%20a%20fallacy%2C%20it%20is%20submitted%2C%20points%20to%20no%20fallacy%20at%20all%2C%20for%20the%20only%20justification%20the%20Court%20finds%20for%20repelling%20this%20argument%20is%20an%20unreasoned%20pursuit%20of%20an%20omnipotent%20ED.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EConclusion%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20instant%20case%2C%20therefore%2C%20has%20the%20effect%20of%20further%20entrenching%20the%20ED%E2%80%99s%20illegibility%2C%20which%20%E2%80%93%C2%A0when%20seen%20with%20%3Cem%3EChoudhary%3C%2Fem%3E%20%E2%80%93%20creates%20an%20entity%20with%20the%20following%20characteristics%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Col%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EThe%20ED%20is%20generally%20not%20the%20police%20(%3Cem%3EChoudhary%2C%3C%2Fem%3E%20%5B438%5D).%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EThe%20ED%20is%20a%20court%20for%20the%20purposes%20of%20summons%20under%20Section%2050%20of%20the%20PMLA%20and%20can%20compel%20one%20to%20answer%20its%20questions%2C%20and%20can%20prosecute%20one%20for%20perjury%20for%20lying%20to%20it.%20(%3Cem%3EChoudhary%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20%5B431%5D)%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EThe%20ED%20can%2C%20during%20the%20stage%20of%20summons%2C%20extract%20confessions%20from%20an%20accused%2C%20which%20would%20be%20relevant%20under%20Section%2025%20of%20the%20IEA.%20This%20is%20because%20of%20(1)%20%E2%80%93%20the%20fact%20that%20the%20ED%20is%20%3Cem%3Enot%3C%2Fem%3E%20the%20police.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EThe%20ED%20can%20validly%20effect%20arrest%20under%20Section%2019%20of%20the%20PMLA%20when%20it%20has%20%E2%80%9Creason%20to%20believe%E2%80%9D%20that%20a%20person%20is%20guilty%20of%20an%20offence%20under%20the%20PMLA%20(%3Cem%3EChoudhary%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20%5B322%5D).%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EAfter%20the%20ED%20arrests%2C%20Section%2025%20of%20the%20IEA%20somehow%20becomes%20applicable%2C%20though%20the%20ED%20still%20isn%E2%80%99t%20the%20police%20(%3Cem%3EChoudhary%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20%5B431%5D).%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EDespite%20the%20occurrence%20of%20the%20substantial%20interrogation%20in%20(2)%20that%20would%20have%20created%20the%20%E2%80%9Creason%20to%20believe%E2%80%9D%20in%20(4)%2C%20and%20the%20post-arrest%20%E2%80%9Cpolice%E2%80%9D%20character%20of%20the%20ED%20in%20(5)%2C%20the%20ED%20still%20isn%E2%80%99t%20the%20police%20(%3Cem%3EBalaji%3C%2Fem%3E%20%5B84%5D)%2C%20but%20is%20entitled%20to%20custody%20u%2Fs%20167(2)%20(%3Cem%3EBalaji%3C%2Fem%3E%20%5B85%5D).%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3C%2Fol%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThis%20state%20of%20affairs%2C%20to%20say%20the%20least%2C%20is%20highly%20incoherent%20and%20unprincipled%20%E2%80%93%C2%A0%3Cem%3EChoudhary%3C%2Fem%3E%20was%20premised%20on%20strengthening%20the%20ED%20to%20the%20greatest%20possible%20extent%2C%20creating%20an%20entity%20that%20is%20deliberately%20illegible%20in%20law%2C%20with%20the%20court%20sitting%20comfortably%20with%20its%20shapeshifting%20character.%20The%20instant%20case%20builds%20on%20this%20illegibility%20%E2%80%93%20entrenching%20it%20deeper%20instead%20of%20attempting%20to%20escape%20it.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EKartik%20Kalra%20is%20a%20student%20at%20the%20National%20Law%20School%20of%20India%20University%2C%20Bengaluru.%C2%A0%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1693313055000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F08%2F29180215%2FThe-Wire-1.png%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Flaw%2Fsenthil-balaji-case-sc-verdict-cements-eds-illegibility-in-law-its-power-to-take-custody%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22The%20ED's%20power%20to%20obtain%20custody%20had%20to%20be%20navigated%20in%20light%20of%20the%20court's%20previous%20verdict%20in%20the%20'Vijay%20Madanlal%20Choudhary'%20case%2C%20which%20denied%20the%20ED%20the%20status%20of%20the%20police%20to%20foreclose%20the%20application%20of%20the%20right%20against%20self-incrimination.%20It%20constituted%20the%20ED%20as%20an%20illegible%20entity%2C%20somewhere%20between%20the%20court%20and%20the%20police.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A0%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fthewire.in%2Flaw%2Fsenthil-balaji-case-sc-verdict-cements-eds-illegibility-in-law-its-power-to-take-custody%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Road%2C%20renewables%20capex%20likely%20to%20rise%20by%2035%25%20in%20FY24%20%26amp%3B%20FY25%3A%20CRISIL%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%22%2C%22published%22%3A1693312908000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fbsmedia.business-standard.com%2F_media%2Fbs%2Fimg%2Farticle%2F2022-06%2F03%2Ffull%2F1654272617-2588.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.business-standard.com%2Feconomy%2Fnews%2Fro